Red Wine Quality : An Exploratory Data Analysis by Nupur Shukla

Introduction

The objective of this analyis is to use Exploratory Data Analysis techniques to find “Which chemical properties influence the quality of wine ?” Being a wine enthusiast myself, I have experienced the price of wine largely depends on it’s propularity otr appreciation in the social circle.I chose this dataset for analysis because I am interested to see whether human tasting can be related to the chemical properties of wine. This analysis can be used to further build a predictive model which can provide guidance to vineyards regarding the price and quality of of their wines.

The Data Set

This tidy data set contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Transforming data

In order to reduce the skewness of variables; Residual Sugar, Chlorides, Free Sulfur Dioxide, Total Sulfur Dioxide and Sulphates a log transformation is applied to make this distribution more “Normal”. Skew data can be transformed to have a more normal distribution (ideal for linear or logistic regression model ) using log or square root transformation techniques. The histogram for Citirc Acid shows the distribution is not normal, a log transformation resulted in a left skewed distribution for this variable so I have applied a square root transformation to get a more normal looking plot except the spike at 0. The plots can be found below :

Internet articles suggest a good sign of quality is balance.A wine is balanced when all of the wine’s components (e.g. sweetness, acidity, tannins, alcohol) blend together. The balance or potential to be balanced after ageing is a sign of quality. Next, Let’s create a categorical variable to distinguish ‘loW’(score<5), ‘medium’(5==8) quality wines.

# Adding a new feature wine_category which distinguishes wines into 3 categories
red_wine$wine_category<-0
red_wine$wine_category<-ifelse(red_wine$quality<5,'low',red_wine$wine_category)
red_wine$wine_category<-ifelse((red_wine$quality>=5 & red_wine$quality<7) ,
                               'medium',red_wine$wine_category)
red_wine$wine_category<-ifelse(red_wine$quality>=7 ,'high',
                               red_wine$wine_category)
red_wine$wine_category<-ordered(red_wine$wine_category,levels=c('low','medium',
                                                                'high'))

The Barplot above clearly indicates that maximum samples in this data set are of medium quality. Since, quality is indicating the wine category I will now convert quality into a factor variable.

red_wine$quality_factor<-factor(red_wine$quality)

Regression Model

I will now create a linear regression model to predict wine quality.All variables are added to the model in progression( according to their relationship with quality).

m1<-lm(data=red_wine,quality~volatile.acidity)
m2<-update(m1,~.+alcohol)
m3<-update(m2,~.+sulphates)
m4<-update(m3,~.+citric.acid)
m5<-update(m4,~.+chlorides+total.sulfur.dioxide+density+fixed.acidity)
mtable(m1,m2,m3,m4,m5)

Reflection

This dataset contained 1,599 observations of red wines. Each wine received a quality rating and had information on 11 different chemical attributes. Most of the analysis in this project was done on the 4 feautres ( alcohol(0.476), volatile acidity(-0.39), sulphates(0.251), citric acid(0.226)) that have the highest correlation with quality. Apart form these, some features showed interesting relationships and patterns in wine quality when plotted against each other for example, Density vs Fixed acidity (plot 2) and Volatile acidity vs alcohol(plot 3).

In the end , I created a regression model progressively adding the top 4 features mentioned above. Alcohol, volatile acidity and sulphates show highest correlation with quality but this model(m3) is able to explain only 33.6% of the existing cases. Also, addition of citric acid (m4) did not change the r-squared value at all. However, adding some variables with some correlation with quality improved the value t0 35.6%.

One of the major challenges in this analysis was the limitations of the dataset. The sign of quality in wines is when all components ( sweetness,acidity,tannins) blend together.Maturity, colour (depending on different grape varities), climatic conditions (The higher the level of sugar in the grapes before fermentation, the higher potential alcohol the wine will have, i.e. hotter countries tend to produce wines higher in alcohol), viticulture (way grapes are grown) and vinification (winemaking) are some important factors that effect the quality of wine and cannot be captured by chemical attribute variables.Also,Current data consists of samples collected from a s pecific portugal region.It will be intresting to obtain datasets across various wine making regions to eliminate any bias created by any secific qualities of the product.

Further analyis can be useful in creating a more sophisticated prediction model for wine quality if mmore data of extreme quality cases (both high and low-quality) along with non-chemical attributes can be collected.
